<p>For cooling applications, Indiana homeowners should consider air conditioning systems with SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) ratings of at least 14-16, though systems with SEER ratings of 18-22 provide optimal efficiency and long-term savings. High-efficiency heat pumps are increasingly popular in Indiana, particularly in central and southern regions where winter temperatures remain moderate enough for heat pump operation. For northern Indiana, hybrid heat pump systems or high-efficiency gas furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher are recommended for reliable winter heating.</p>

<p>Humidity control is a critical consideration for Indiana HVAC systems, as excessive moisture can lead to comfort issues and indoor air quality problems. Variable-speed air handlers and properly sized equipment help maintain optimal humidity levels while maximizing energy efficiency. Whole-house dehumidification systems are often beneficial additions to traditional HVAC equipment, particularly in newer, well-sealed homes where natural ventilation is limited.</p>

