<h2>Indiana Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Indiana offers several attractive incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems. The most substantial benefit comes from the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the total solar installation cost from their federal taxes. This credit applies to all system components, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to \$6,000 in tax savings, making it the single most valuable incentive available to Indiana residents.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Tax Credit (30%):</strong> Available through 2032, this credit allows homeowners to claim 30% of their total solar installation costs against federal income taxes. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability, ensuring maximum benefit regardless of individual tax situations.</li>
<li><strong>Indiana Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar energy systems are exempt from property tax assessments in Indiana, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase annual property tax bills. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the system.</li>
<li><strong>Duke Energy Indiana Rebates:</strong> Duke Energy offers various rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment, including \$50-200 rebates for high-efficiency air conditioners and heat pumps, and up to \$400 for qualifying smart thermostats and whole-house efficiency upgrades.</li>
<li><strong>Local Municipal Incentives:</strong> Several Indiana cities and counties offer additional incentives, including expedited permitting for solar installations, reduced permit fees, and local rebate programs. Indianapolis, Fort Wayne, and Bloomington have particularly active programs supporting renewable energy adoption.</li>
<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> Indiana's net metering law allows solar customers to receive retail rate credits for excess electricity generated by their systems, effectively using the utility grid as a battery for storing surplus production during peak generation periods.</li>
</ul>

